{"title_page": "Spivy", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Spivy\n| image         = File:Requiem for a Heavyweight (1962) trailer 2.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Spivy (left) with [[Stanley Adams (actor)|Stanley Adams]] in the 1962 film ''Requiem for a Heavyweight''\n| birth_name    = Bertha Levine\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1906|09|30}}\n| birth_place   = Brooklyn, New York, U.S.\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1971|01|07|1906|09|30}} \n| death_place   = Los Angeles, California, U.S.\n| nationality   = American\n| other_names   = Spivy Levoe, Spivy Le Voe, Madame Spivy\n| occupation    = Entertainer, actress\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = }}\n\n'''Bertha Levine''' (September 30, 1906 \u2013 January 7, 1971),<ref name=CDI />{{refn|name=dates|group=Note|Most sources, including the New York Birth Index,<ref name=\"NYBI\">{{cite web |title=New York, New York, Extracted Birth Index, 1878-1909 |url=https://www.ancestry.com.au/inst/discoveries/PfRecord?emailId=N-92112b96-74f1-453c-adf9-b2e20c39897e&collectionId=9089&recordId=356322&ahsht=2019-11-04T00:22:41&language=en-AU&ahsh=db61f9c75422d7bc50fb7ddd003300b0 |website=Ancestry.com |accessdate=4 November 2019}} Surname misspelled as Levene.</ref> support the 1906 birth year,  although a few state 1907. The ''California Death Index'' records her date of death as Thursday, January 7, 1971. Some sources, including Gavin (2006) and her ''New York Times'' obituary, state she died January 8.}} who used the stage name '''Spivy''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|p|\u026a|v|i}} {{Respell|SPIH|vee|}}),<ref>{{cite web|title=Say How?|url=https://www.loc.gov/nls/about/organization/standards-guidelines/qrst/#s|website=National Library Service for the Blind and Physically Handicapped|publisher=Library of Congress|accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref>  was an American entertainer, nightclub owner, and actress.<ref name=NYT>{{cite news|title=Spivy, 64, Actress and Entertainer|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/01/10/archives/pinn-6-agtress-and-htertaiher-owner-of-nightclubs-here-and-abroad.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=10 January 1971}}</ref><ref name=Gavin>{{cite book|last1=Gavin|first1=James|title=Intimate Nights: the Golden Age of New York Cabaret|date=2006|publisher=Back Stage Books|isbn=9780823088256|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/intimatenightsgo00gavi_0}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life===\n'''Bertha Levine''' was born in Brooklyn, New York, in 1906, the eldest of the four daughters of Louis and Helen Levine, Jewish immigrants from Russia.<ref name=Pollack /><ref name=NYT /><ref>{{cite web|title=United States Census, 1930|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:X4J2-QVP|website=FamilySearch|accessdate=2 April 2018}}   {{registration}}</ref><ref name=\"Drutman\">{{cite book |last1=Drutman |first1=Irving |title=Good Company: A Memoir, Mostly Theatrical |date=1976 |publisher=Little, Brown & Co. |page=[https://archive.org/details/goodcompanymemoi00drut/page/213 213] |url=https://archive.org/details/goodcompanymemoi00drut|url-access=registration }}</ref> She played organ in churches and theaters before establishing a career as a singer-pianist in [[speakeasies]] and nightclubs under the name Spivy Le Voe, which she later shortened to '''Spivy'''.<ref name=Pollack /> Her stage name was reportedly based on a younger sister's mispronunciation of the word \"sister.\"<ref name=Gavin />{{Rp|31}}\n\n===Performing career===\nIn 1936 she became a regular act at Tony's, a New York nightclub on West 52nd Street, where she performed satirical songs, some of which were written by [[John La Touche (lyricist)|John Latouche]] and [[Jill Rainsford]].<ref name=Pollack /><ref>{{cite web|title=Guide to the Jill \"Billy\" Rainsford Papers (1922-1991)|url=http://dlib.nyu.edu/findingaids/html/fales/rainsford/bioghist.html|website=Fales Library & Special Collections|publisher=New York University Libraries|accessdate=7 April 2018}}</ref> In 1939, the ''[[New York Times]]'' wrote that \"Spivy's material, witty, acid, and tragicomic, is better than most of the essays one hears about town, and her delivery is that of a sophisticated artist on her own grounds. She knows the value of surprise in punching a line, she uses understatement unerringly, and her piano accompaniment is superb.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Strauss|first1=Theodore|title=News of Night Clubs|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1939/11/19/archives/news-of-night-clubs-various-matters-concerned-with-places-to-be.html|work=[[New York Times]]|date=November 19, 1939|page=2X|language=en}} {{subscription}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1940\u20131951 she ran her own nightclub, Spivy's Roof, on New York's [[East 57th Street]].<ref name=Pollack>{{cite book|last1=Pollack|first1=Howard|title=The Ballad of John Latouche: An American Lyricist's Life and Work|date=2017|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780190458300|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Jpc4DwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA41&dq=spivy&pg=PA41#v=onepage&q=spivy&f=false|language=en}}</ref>  The club was noted for its tolerance of gay performers and patrons; Spivy herself was a lesbian in private life. Among the artists who performed there were [[Mabel Mercer]], [[Thelma Carpenter]], [[Paul Lynde]], [[Martha Raye]],  [[Liberace]], and actor-magician [[Fred Keating]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Chauncey|first1=George|title=Gay New York: Gender, Urban Culture, and the Making of the Gay Male World, 1890-1940|date=2008|publisher=Basic Books|isbn=9780786723355|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RXI4DgAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&dq=gay%20new%20york%20chauncey&pg=PT239#v=onepage&q=spivy&f=false|language=en}}</ref><ref name=Gavin /><ref>{{cite book|last1=Pyron|first1=Darden Asbury|title=Liberace: An American Boy|date=2013|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=9780226117126|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RCSkGd_2zRIC&lpg=PA97&dq=spivy&pg=PA97#v=onepage&q=spivy&f=false|language=en}}</ref>\nAlthough it was reported that Spivy and Keating intended to marry on Christmas Eve 1942,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kilgallen|first1=Dorothy|authorlink1=Dorothy Kilgallen|title=The Voice of Broadway|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspapers%252023%2FElmira%2520%2520NY%2520Star%2520Gazette%2FElmira%2520NY%2520Star%2520Gazette%25201942%2FElmira%2520NY%2520Star%2520Gazette%25201942%2520-%25205767.pdf%23xml%3Dhttp%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3D7a1121d3%26DocId%3D2275649%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cDISK%2520S%26HitCount%3D6%26hits%3D87e%2B98b%2B98d%2B98e%2B99a%2Bbd6%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&uri=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspapers%252023%2FElmira%2520%2520NY%2520Star%2520Gazette%2FElmira%2520NY%2520Star%2520Gazette%25201942%2FElmira%2520NY%2520Star%2520Gazette%25201942%2520-%25205767.pdf&xml=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3D7a1121d3%26DocId%3D2275649%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cDISK%2520S%26HitCount%3D6%26hits%3D87e%2B98b%2B98d%2B98e%2B99a%2Bbd6%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&openFirstHlPage=false|work=[[Elmira Star-Gazette]]|date=December 14, 1942|page=6|quote=Is it a gag, or are Spivy and Fred Keating serious when they invite friends to their 'wedding on Christmas Eve?'}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Wilson|first1=Earl|authorlink1=Earl Wilson (columnist)|title=Spivy at Folies Bergere|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252011%2FNew%2520York%2520Evening%2520Post%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Evening%2520Post%25201943%2520Grayscale%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Evening%2520Post%25201943%2520a%2520Grayscale%2520-%25206688.pdf%23xml%3Dhttp%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3Dffffffffff86f02c%26DocId%3D5574691%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cIndex%2520U%252dF%252dP%26HitCount%3D8%26hits%3D2a%2B18b%2B1b8%2B1cd%2B1e5%2B216%2B243%2B248%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&uri=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252011%2FNew%2520York%2520Evening%2520Post%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Evening%2520Post%25201943%2520Grayscale%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Evening%2520Post%25201943%2520a%2520Grayscale%2520-%25206688.pdf&xml=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3Dffffffffff86f02c%26DocId%3D5574691%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cIndex%2520U%252dF%252dP%26HitCount%3D8%26hits%3D2a%2B18b%2B1b8%2B1cd%2B1e5%2B216%2B243%2B248%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&openFirstHlPage=false|work=[[New York Post]]|date=September 3, 1943|page=29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kilgallen |first1=Dorothy |authorlink1=Dorothy Kilgallen |title=The Voice of Broadway |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26205093/ |work=[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]] |date=December 29, 1942 |quote=Spivy and magician Fred Keating have postponed their wedding because of her father's illness|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> this appears to have been a publicity stunt or [[lavender marriage]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kilgallen|first1=Dorothy|authorlink1=Dorothy Kilgallen|title=The Voice of Broadway|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FOlean%2520NY%2520Times%2520Herald%2FOlean%2520NY%2520Times%2520Herald%25201944%2FOlean%2520NY%2520Times%2520Herald%25201944%2520%2528110%2529_1.pdf%23xml%3Dhttp%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3Dffffffff9032d6a8%26DocId%3D2964478%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cDISK%2520X%26HitCount%3D5%26hits%3D924%2B929%2B92a%2B92c%2B937%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&uri=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FOlean%2520NY%2520Times%2520Herald%2FOlean%2520NY%2520Times%2520Herald%25201944%2FOlean%2520NY%2520Times%2520Herald%25201944%2520%2528110%2529_1.pdf&xml=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3Dffffffff9032d6a8%26DocId%3D2964478%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cDISK%2520X%26HitCount%3D5%26hits%3D924%2B929%2B92a%2B92c%2B937%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&openFirstHlPage=false|work=[[Olean Times Herald]]|date=January 27, 1944|page=8|quote=Although married, Fred Keating and Spivy occupy separate domiciles and only appear together formally at Spivy's Roof.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Oakley Christoph |first1=M. |title=Informing You |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26205423/ |work=[[Hartford Courant]] |date=April 18, 1944 |page=9 |quote=Fred Keating... said, when we asked him if he was married to Spivy, 'People say so'...|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\nShe released two [[78 rpm]] albums of songs,<ref name=Pollack /> which have never been reissued on CD. Her recordings indicate that her performing style was to \"recite\" (rather than sing) the lyrics over piano accompaniment.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Aston|first1=Martin|title=How music came out: 15 records by unsung LGBTQ+ pioneers|url=https://thevinylfactory.com/features/15-records-unsung-lgbtq-pioneers/|website=The Vinyl Factory|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171025005829/https://thevinylfactory.com/features/15-records-unsung-lgbtq-pioneers/|archivedate=25 October 2017|date=24 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Later acting career===\nIn the 1950s, Spivy spent several years touring Paris, London, and Rome before returning to the U.S. in 1957, where she embarked on a new career as a [[character actor]], usually billed as Madame Spivy.<ref name=Gavin /> She had supporting roles in the films ''[[The Fugitive Kind]], [[Studs Lonigan]], [[All Fall Down (1962 film)|All Fall Down]], [[Requiem for a Heavyweight]]'', and ''[[The Manchurian Candidate (1962 film)|The Manchurian Candidate]]'', where her stout physique led to her being cast as matronly or villainous characters.{{refn|group=Note|Gavin (2006) states she also appeared in 1962's ''[[Walk on the Wild Side (film)|Walk on the Wild Side]]'', but this is not corroborated by other sources.}} She also appeared on stage in a Broadway production of ''[[Auntie Mame]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Spivy \u2013 Broadway Cast & Staff|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/spivy-101475|website=Internet Broadway Database|accessdate=2 April 2018}}</ref> Her best-remembered television appearance is  a darkly humorous episode of ''[[Alfred Hitchcock Presents]]'' (1959's \"The Specialty of the House\"), in which she played the manager of a restaurant whose unsuspecting guests implicitly end up on the menu.<ref name=Gavin />\n\n===Death===\nBy 1969, Spivy had been diagnosed with cancer. Her friend [[Patsy Kelly]] arranged for her to move into the   [[Motion Picture Country Home]] in [[Woodland Hills, Los Angeles]],<ref name= Gavin /><ref name=NYT /> where she died on January 7, 1971, aged 64.<ref name=CDI>{{cite web|title=California Death Index, 1940-1997|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:VPK1-SGC|website=FamilySearch|accessdate=2 April 2018}} {{registration}}</ref><ref group=\"Note\" name=\"dates\" />\n\n==Discography==\n*''Seven Gay Sophisticated Songs by Spivy'' (1939)<ref>{{cite web|title=Spivy - Seven Gay Sophisticated Songs By Spivy|url=https://www.discogs.com/Spivy-Seven-Gay-Sophisticated-Songs-By-Spivy/release/9417532|website=Discogs|accessdate=2 April 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n*''An Evening with Spivy'' (1947)<ref name=Pollack />\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1960|| ''[[The Fugitive Kind]]'' || Ruby Lightfoot ||\n|-\n|1960|| ''[[Studs Lonigan]]'' || Mother Josephine ||\n|-\n|1962|| ''[[All Fall Down (1962 film)|All Fall Down]]'' || Bouncer ||\n|-\n|1962|| ''[[Requiem for a Heavyweight#Film_version|Requiem for a Heavyweight]]'' || Ma Greeny ||\n|-\n|1962|| ''[[The Manchurian Candidate (1962 film)|The Manchurian Candidate]]'' || Female Berezovo ||\n|}\n\n==Selected television appearances==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Series\n! Episode\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1959|| ''[[Alfred Hitchcock Presents]]'' ||[[List_of_Alfred_Hitchcock_Presents_episodes#Season_5_(1959%E2%80%9360)|The Specialty of the House]]|| Spirro ||\n|-\n\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name}}\n*{{Find a Grave}}\n*[http://queermusicheritage.com/oct2000ms.html Queer Music Heritage]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1971 deaths]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Jewish American actresses]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Nightclub owners]]\n[[Category:LGBT actresses]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Spivy\n| image         = File:Requiem for a Heavyweight (1962) trailer 2.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Spivy (left) with [[Stanley Adams (actor)|Stanley Adams]] in the 1962 film ''Requiem for a Heavyweight''\n| birth_name    = Bertha Levine\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1906|09|30}}\n| birth_place   = Brooklyn, New York, U.S.\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1971|01|07|1906|09|30}} \n| death_place   = Los Angeles, California, U.S.\n| nationality   = American\n| other_names   = Spivy Levoe, Spivy Le Voe, Madame Spivy\n| occupation    = Entertainer, actress\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = }}\n\n'''Bertha Levine''' (September 30, 1906 \u2013 January 7, 1971),<ref name=CDI />{{refn|name=dates|group=Note|Most sources, including the New York Birth Index,<ref name=\"NYBI\">{{cite web |title=New York, New York, Extracted Birth Index, 1878-1909 |url=https://www.ancestry.com.au/inst/discoveries/PfRecord?emailId=N-92112b96-74f1-453c-adf9-b2e20c39897e&collectionId=9089&recordId=356322&ahsht=2019-11-04T00:22:41&language=en-AU&ahsh=db61f9c75422d7bc50fb7ddd003300b0 |website=Ancestry.com |accessdate=4 November 2019}} Surname misspelled as Levene.</ref> support the 1906 birth year,  although a few state 1907. The ''California Death Index'' records her date of death as Thursday, January 7, 1971. Some sources, including Gavin (2006) and her ''New York Times'' obituary, state she died January 8.}} who used the stage name '''Spivy''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|p|\u026a|v|i}} {{Respell|SPIH|vee|}}),<ref>{{cite web|title=Say How?|url=https://www.loc.gov/nls/about/organization/standards-guidelines/qrst/#s|website=National Library Service for the Blind and Physically Handicapped|publisher=Library of Congress|accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref>  was an American entertainer, nightclub owner, and actress.<ref name=NYT>{{cite news|title=Spivy, 64, Actress and Entertainer|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/01/10/archives/pinn-6-agtress-and-htertaiher-owner-of-nightclubs-here-and-abroad.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=10 January 1971}}</ref><ref name=Gavin>{{cite book|last1=Gavin|first1=James|title=Intimate Nights: the Golden Age of New York Cabaret|date=2006|publisher=Back Stage Books|isbn=9780823088256|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/intimatenightsgo00gavi_0}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life===\n'''Bertha Levine''' was born in Brooklyn, New York in 1906, the eldest of the four daughters of Louis and Helen Levine, Jewish immigrants from Russia.<ref name=Pollack /><ref name=NYT /><ref>{{cite web|title=United States Census, 1930|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:X4J2-QVP|website=FamilySearch|accessdate=2 April 2018}}   {{registration}}</ref><ref name=\"Drutman\">{{cite book |last1=Drutman |first1=Irving |title=Good Company: A Memoir, Mostly Theatrical |date=1976 |publisher=Little, Brown & Co. |page=[https://archive.org/details/goodcompanymemoi00drut/page/213 213] |url=https://archive.org/details/goodcompanymemoi00drut|url-access=registration }}</ref> She played organ in churches and theaters before establishing a career as a singer-pianist in [[speakeasies]] and nightclubs under the name Spivy Le Voe, which she later shortened to '''Spivy'''.<ref name=Pollack /> Her stage name was reportedly based on a younger sister's mispronunciation of the word \"sister.\"<ref name=Gavin />{{Rp|31}}\n\n===Performing career===\nIn 1936 she became a regular act at Tony's, a New York nightclub on West 52nd Street, where she performed satirical songs, some of which were written by [[John La Touche (lyricist)|John Latouche]] and [[Jill Rainsford]].<ref name=Pollack /><ref>{{cite web|title=Guide to the Jill \"Billy\" Rainsford Papers (1922-1991)|url=http://dlib.nyu.edu/findingaids/html/fales/rainsford/bioghist.html|website=Fales Library & Special Collections|publisher=New York University Libraries|accessdate=7 April 2018}}</ref> In 1939, the ''[[New York Times]]'' wrote that \"Spivy's material, witty, acid, and tragicomic, is better than most of the essays one hears about town, and her delivery is that of a sophisticated artist on her own grounds. She knows the value of surprise in punching a line, she uses understatement unerringly, and her piano accompaniment is superb.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Strauss|first1=Theodore|title=News of Night Clubs|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1939/11/19/archives/news-of-night-clubs-various-matters-concerned-with-places-to-be.html|work=[[New York Times]]|date=November 19, 1939|page=2X|language=en}} {{subscription}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1940\u20131951 she ran her own nightclub, Spivy's Roof, on New York's [[East 57th Street]].<ref name=Pollack>{{cite book|last1=Pollack|first1=Howard|title=The Ballad of John Latouche: An American Lyricist's Life and Work|date=2017|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780190458300|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Jpc4DwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA41&dq=spivy&pg=PA41#v=onepage&q=spivy&f=false|language=en}}</ref>  The club was noted for its tolerance of gay performers and patrons; Spivy herself was a lesbian in private life. Among the artists who performed there were [[Mabel Mercer]], [[Thelma Carpenter]], [[Paul Lynde]], [[Martha Raye]],  [[Liberace]], and actor-magician [[Fred Keating]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Chauncey|first1=George|title=Gay New York: Gender, Urban Culture, and the Making of the Gay Male World, 1890-1940|date=2008|publisher=Basic Books|isbn=9780786723355|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RXI4DgAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&dq=gay%20new%20york%20chauncey&pg=PT239#v=onepage&q=spivy&f=false|language=en}}</ref><ref name=Gavin /><ref>{{cite book|last1=Pyron|first1=Darden Asbury|title=Liberace: An American Boy|date=2013|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=9780226117126|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RCSkGd_2zRIC&lpg=PA97&dq=spivy&pg=PA97#v=onepage&q=spivy&f=false|language=en}}</ref>\nAlthough it was reported that Spivy and Keating intended to marry on Christmas Eve 1942,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kilgallen|first1=Dorothy|authorlink1=Dorothy Kilgallen|title=The Voice of Broadway|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspapers%252023%2FElmira%2520%2520NY%2520Star%2520Gazette%2FElmira%2520NY%2520Star%2520Gazette%25201942%2FElmira%2520NY%2520Star%2520Gazette%25201942%2520-%25205767.pdf%23xml%3Dhttp%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3D7a1121d3%26DocId%3D2275649%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cDISK%2520S%26HitCount%3D6%26hits%3D87e%2B98b%2B98d%2B98e%2B99a%2Bbd6%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&uri=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspapers%252023%2FElmira%2520%2520NY%2520Star%2520Gazette%2FElmira%2520NY%2520Star%2520Gazette%25201942%2FElmira%2520NY%2520Star%2520Gazette%25201942%2520-%25205767.pdf&xml=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3D7a1121d3%26DocId%3D2275649%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cDISK%2520S%26HitCount%3D6%26hits%3D87e%2B98b%2B98d%2B98e%2B99a%2Bbd6%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&openFirstHlPage=false|work=[[Elmira Star-Gazette]]|date=December 14, 1942|page=6|quote=Is it a gag, or are Spivy and Fred Keating serious when they invite friends to their 'wedding on Christmas Eve?'}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Wilson|first1=Earl|authorlink1=Earl Wilson (columnist)|title=Spivy at Folies Bergere|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252011%2FNew%2520York%2520Evening%2520Post%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Evening%2520Post%25201943%2520Grayscale%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Evening%2520Post%25201943%2520a%2520Grayscale%2520-%25206688.pdf%23xml%3Dhttp%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3Dffffffffff86f02c%26DocId%3D5574691%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cIndex%2520U%252dF%252dP%26HitCount%3D8%26hits%3D2a%2B18b%2B1b8%2B1cd%2B1e5%2B216%2B243%2B248%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&uri=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252011%2FNew%2520York%2520Evening%2520Post%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Evening%2520Post%25201943%2520Grayscale%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Evening%2520Post%25201943%2520a%2520Grayscale%2520-%25206688.pdf&xml=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3Dffffffffff86f02c%26DocId%3D5574691%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cIndex%2520U%252dF%252dP%26HitCount%3D8%26hits%3D2a%2B18b%2B1b8%2B1cd%2B1e5%2B216%2B243%2B248%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&openFirstHlPage=false|work=[[New York Post]]|date=September 3, 1943|page=29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kilgallen |first1=Dorothy |authorlink1=Dorothy Kilgallen |title=The Voice of Broadway |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26205093/ |work=[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]] |date=December 29, 1942 |quote=Spivy and magician Fred Keating have postponed their wedding because of her father's illness|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> this appears to have been a publicity stunt or [[lavender marriage]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kilgallen|first1=Dorothy|authorlink1=Dorothy Kilgallen|title=The Voice of Broadway|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FOlean%2520NY%2520Times%2520Herald%2FOlean%2520NY%2520Times%2520Herald%25201944%2FOlean%2520NY%2520Times%2520Herald%25201944%2520%2528110%2529_1.pdf%23xml%3Dhttp%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3Dffffffff9032d6a8%26DocId%3D2964478%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cDISK%2520X%26HitCount%3D5%26hits%3D924%2B929%2B92a%2B92c%2B937%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&uri=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FOlean%2520NY%2520Times%2520Herald%2FOlean%2520NY%2520Times%2520Herald%25201944%2FOlean%2520NY%2520Times%2520Herald%25201944%2520%2528110%2529_1.pdf&xml=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3Dffffffff9032d6a8%26DocId%3D2964478%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cDISK%2520X%26HitCount%3D5%26hits%3D924%2B929%2B92a%2B92c%2B937%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&openFirstHlPage=false|work=[[Olean Times Herald]]|date=January 27, 1944|page=8|quote=Although married, Fred Keating and Spivy occupy separate domiciles and only appear together formally at Spivy's Roof.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Oakley Christoph |first1=M. |title=Informing You |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26205423/ |work=[[Hartford Courant]] |date=April 18, 1944 |page=9 |quote=Fred Keating... said, when we asked him if he was married to Spivy, 'People say so'...|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\nShe released two [[78 rpm]] albums of songs,<ref name=Pollack /> which have never been reissued on CD. Her recordings indicate that her performing style was to \"recite\" (rather than sing) the lyrics over piano accompaniment.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Aston|first1=Martin|title=How music came out: 15 records by unsung LGBTQ+ pioneers|url=https://thevinylfactory.com/features/15-records-unsung-lgbtq-pioneers/|website=The Vinyl Factory|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171025005829/https://thevinylfactory.com/features/15-records-unsung-lgbtq-pioneers/|archivedate=25 October 2017|date=24 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Later acting career===\nIn the 1950s, Spivy spent several years touring Paris, London, and Rome before returning to the U.S. in 1957, where she embarked on a new career as a [[character actor]], usually billed as Madame Spivy.<ref name=Gavin /> She had supporting roles in the films ''[[The Fugitive Kind]], [[Studs Lonigan]], [[All Fall Down (1962 film)|All Fall Down]], [[Requiem for a Heavyweight]]'', and ''[[The Manchurian Candidate (1962 film)|The Manchurian Candidate]]'', where her stout physique led to her being cast as matronly or villainous characters.{{refn|group=Note|Gavin (2006) states she also appeared in 1962's ''[[Walk on the Wild Side (film)|Walk on the Wild Side]]'', but this is not corroborated by other sources.}} She also appeared on stage in a Broadway production of ''[[Auntie Mame]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Spivy \u2013 Broadway Cast & Staff|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/spivy-101475|website=Internet Broadway Database|accessdate=2 April 2018}}</ref> Her best-remembered television appearance is  a darkly humorous episode of ''[[Alfred Hitchcock Presents]]'' (1959's \"The Specialty of the House\"), in which she played the manager of a restaurant whose unsuspecting guests implicitly end up on the menu.<ref name=Gavin />\n\n===Death===\nBy 1969, Spivy had been diagnosed with cancer. Her friend [[Patsy Kelly]] arranged for her to move into the   [[Motion Picture Country Home]] in [[Woodland Hills, Los Angeles]],<ref name= Gavin /><ref name=NYT /> where she died on January 7, 1971, aged 64.<ref name=CDI>{{cite web|title=California Death Index, 1940-1997|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:VPK1-SGC|website=FamilySearch|accessdate=2 April 2018}} {{registration}}</ref><ref group=\"Note\" name=\"dates\" />\n\n==Discography==\n*''Seven Gay Sophisticated Songs by Spivy'' (1939)<ref>{{cite web|title=Spivy - Seven Gay Sophisticated Songs By Spivy|url=https://www.discogs.com/Spivy-Seven-Gay-Sophisticated-Songs-By-Spivy/release/9417532|website=Discogs|accessdate=2 April 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n*''An Evening with Spivy'' (1947)<ref name=Pollack />\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1960|| ''[[The Fugitive Kind]]'' || Ruby Lightfoot ||\n|-\n|1960|| ''[[Studs Lonigan]]'' || Mother Josephine ||\n|-\n|1962|| ''[[All Fall Down (1962 film)|All Fall Down]]'' || Bouncer ||\n|-\n|1962|| ''[[Requiem for a Heavyweight#Film_version|Requiem for a Heavyweight]]'' || Ma Greeny ||\n|-\n|1962|| ''[[The Manchurian Candidate (1962 film)|The Manchurian Candidate]]'' || Female Berezovo ||\n|}\n\n==Selected television appearances==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Series\n! Episode\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1959|| ''[[Alfred Hitchcock Presents]]'' ||[[List_of_Alfred_Hitchcock_Presents_episodes#Season_5_(1959%E2%80%9360)|The Specialty of the House]]|| Spirro ||\n|-\n\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name}}\n*{{Find a Grave}}\n*[http://queermusicheritage.com/oct2000ms.html Queer Music Heritage]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1971 deaths]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Jewish American actresses]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Nightclub owners]]\n[[Category:LGBT actresses]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Grammarspellchecker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spivy"}
